post_text:
Reminders from your School Nurses:
Please keep your student home if he/she is ill with two or more symptoms of COVID-19 (headache, nausea/vomiting, diarrhea, sore throat, cough, short of breath, extreme fatigue, chills/shivering/shaking/sweating, new loss of smell/taste, or fever). This is for the health and safety of all students and staff and to help us be in school for as long as we can. We do realize allergy and harvest seasons are upon us and will do our best, however a doctor’s note may be required as proof of alternate diagnosis.
If your student is sent home with two or more symptoms, they are not tested for COVID, and do not have an alternate diagnosis (influenza, strep throat, etc.), the student must remain out of school and all activities for ten days from symptom onset.
These are the guidelines the state of Kansas has set forth for schools to follow as we return to in-person learning.
Thank you for your cooperation,
Erin Winger and Whitney McCauley

post_text:
Hiawatha USD 415 applied for and has been granted a waiver through the USDA extending flexibikities for the Summer Food Service Program (SFSP). With this waiver, the district can choose to operate the SFSP through December 2020.
Q: What does this mean?
A: This means that USD 415 meals can now be served free of charge to ALL students in the district. Each enrolled student of USD 415 can have a free breakfast and free lunch on school days. This program will start Wednesday September 9th and continue through December 2020. Ala carte items at the middle school and high school are not free and must still be purchased by students.

shared_text:
Hiawatha Police Department
June 26 at 12:28 PM ·

If you have driven down Oregon Street today you might have seen some artwork going up in front of the police department. Hiawatha High School’s talented art teacher Matt Leahy and graduating senior Madelyn Gruber are here painting some artwork that Madelyn designed for our department. This was for a high school community service project that was scheduled to be completed last fall. The project had to be postponed last fall and it was again postponed in the spring due to the ongoing COVID issues. This project could have just been forgotten about and left undone but these two are here today on their own time following through with what they started. The east side of the mural has remembrances to Todd M. Widman who lost his life while serving our community. Some say the best way to find yourself is in service to others. Through their artwork and his leadership they are being of service to our community. We wish to say thank you to them! Our community and schools are lucky to have such talented and dedicated teachers like Mr. Leahy.
text:
Hiawatha Police Department
June 26 at 12:28 PM ·

If you have driven down Oregon Street today you might have seen some artwork going up in front of the police department. Hiawatha High School’s talented art teacher Matt Leahy and graduating senior Madelyn Gruber are here painting some artwork that Madelyn designed for our department. This was for a high school community service project that was scheduled to be completed last fall. The project had to be postponed last fall and it was again postponed in the spring due to the ongoing COVID issues. This project could have just been forgotten about and left undone but these two are here today on their own time following through with what they started. The east side of the mural has remembrances to Todd M. Widman who lost his life while serving our community. Some say the best way to find yourself is in service to others. Through their artwork and his leadership they are being of service to our community. We wish to say thank you to them! Our community and schools are lucky to have such talented and dedicated teachers like Mr. Leahy.

Hiawatha Family Clinic has decided that we will offer HHS & HMS sports physicals daily, in the clinic. Scheduled appointments will allow us to provide appropriate protection for athletes, parents, and staff. Students/parents should call the Family Practice (785-742-2161) or the Highland Clinic (785-442-3213) to schedule an appointment. We will also ensure vaccinations are current at this appointment.

KSHSAA Physical forms are available at the clinic.

The Family Practice is open Monday – Friday from 8a – 4p and the Highland Clinic is open Monday – Thursday from 8a – 4p for scheduled appointments.

We ask that all patients/parents adhere to the hospital’s visitor restrictions in place. As of today, only 1 parent per child and face coverings should be worn at all times. All patients and visitors will be screened upon entry which includes a temperature check and questionnaire.

We look forward to serving the student athletes of Hiawatha. Please call the Hiawatha Family Clinic for any questions.

post_text:
Summer Weights and Conditioning will begin the week of June 8th for High School and Middle School GIRLS (2020-2021: 7th-12th Grades.)

We will be offering 2 sessions with limited numbers per session. The first session will be from 9:30-10:45 a.m. and for HS Student-Athletes ONLY. The second session will be from 11:00-12:15 p.m. and open to both JH and HS Girls.

HS Sessions will be offered Monday-Thursday, JH Session on Tuesday & Thursday ONLY.

Cost is $10 for the summer and made payable to HHS. Payment must be given to Mrs. Coach Jasper the first week of sessions.

Per State of Kansas, Brown County Health Department and USD 415, we will be following very strict guidelines to provide a safe and sanitary environment for our athletes and coaches. If you or your daughter are not comfortable participating in our program this summer, please know this is not a mandatory activity.

To sign up, please email Stacy Jasper at sjasper@cityofhiawatha.org or text at 785-632-0604 by Wednesday, June 3rd.
text:
Summer Weights and Conditioning will begin the week of June 8th for High School and Middle School GIRLS (2020-2021: 7th-12th Grades.)

We will be offering 2 sessions with limited numbers per session. The first session will be from 9:30-10:45 a.m. and for HS Student-Athletes ONLY. The second session will be from 11:00-12:15 p.m. and open to both JH and HS Girls.

HS Sessions will be offered Monday-Thursday, JH Session on Tuesday & Thursday ONLY.

Cost is $10 for the summer and made payable to HHS. Payment must be given to Mrs. Coach Jasper the first week of sessions.

Per State of Kansas, Brown County Health Department and USD 415, we will be following very strict guidelines to provide a safe and sanitary environment for our athletes and coaches. If you or your daughter are not comfortable participating in our program this summer, please know this is not a mandatory activity.

To sign up, please email Stacy Jasper at sjasper@cityofhiawatha.org or text at 785-632-0604 by Wednesday, June 3rd.

post_text:
Brown County Sheriff John Merchant is pleased to announce the six deserving 2020 Brown County Sheriff Memorial Scholarship winners. Horton high school seniors, Grady Douglas Miller $1,000.00, Kyle Albert Hammersmith $500.00, Ally Marie Bottom $500.00. Hiawatha high school seniors, Nicole Mackey $1,000.00, Annaliese Elizabeth Jeschke $500.00, Katelyn Lay $500.00. This scholarship is dedicated to all Law Enforcement Officers who have given the ultimate sacrifice in the line of duty. The 6 winners were presented with a Brown County Sheriff challenge coin, a certificate and check. This was the
final year for the Brown County Sheriff Memorial Scholarship. In the future we plan to roll the Brown County Sheriff Memorial Scholarship in to the Deputy Todd Michael Widman Memorial Scholarship. Sheriff Merchant said, “We are so proud to provide these scholarships to our county High School seniors and wish them only the best for their futures."

shared_text:
The Hiawatha ACES
May 12 at 5:25 PM ·

We've had a lot of questions lately, and we are happy to let you know now, that the Summer Lunch Program is a go for June & July!
That being said, things are going to work a little differently this year. As much as we wish we could provide a hot, sit down meal, it just isn't possible this year. We want to be sure that the SLP is as safe as possible for those eating and those volunteering. To this end, for 2020 we will be distributing grab-n-go meals.
These meals will be distributed behind the Sheriff’s Department (south side of the building). We are still working out a few of the details, and will share them with you as soon as we have those all ironed out. Volunteer sign ups will also be available soon.
Thank you all who have inquired - we can't wait to serve you June 2nd!

post_text: Any family with a child(ren) under the age of 5 (up to 58 month) living in USD 415 Hiawatha Schools is now available to receive FREE once a month books mailed directly to their home. Families can build a home library and increase opportunities for language and literacy building. Register your child by going to www.imaginationlibrary.com and clicking on “register my child” You will be prompted to enter your place of residence. Greenbush is acting as an administrator for this project which is being funded by the LINK consortium. If you have any questions regarding registering a child, please contact: Gena Allen (gena.allen@greenbush.org) or by calling 1-800-554-3412

post_text:
Tonight, Friday, April 10 & next Saturday, April 18 Hiawatha High School will be joining other schools around the country by turning on our football stadium lights at 8:20 p.m. which is 20:20 military time. Lights will stay on for 20 minutes & 20 seconds.

At 8:20 p.m. look toward Hiawatha High School to see the glow of our support for our graduating class of 2020.

Please continue to follow CDC guidelines, stay safe & healthy.
